public PropertyChecker.Parameters withSeed(long seed)
        Deprecated. To catch your attention. It's fine to call this method during test debugging, but it should not be committed to version control and used in regression tests, because any changes in the test itself or the framework can render the passed argument obsolete. For regression testing, it's recommended to code the failing scenario explicitly.
        This function allows to start the test with a fixed random seed. It's useful to reproduce some previous test run and debug it.
        Parameters:
        seed - A random seed to use for the first iteration. The following iterations will use other, pseudo-random seeds, but still derived from this one.

      • withSizeHint

        public PropertyChecker.Parameters withSizeHint(@NotNull
                                               IntUnaryOperator sizeHintFun)
        Parameters:
        sizeHintFun - a function determining how size hint should be distributed depending on the iteration number. By default the size hint will be 1 in the first iteration, 2 in the second one, and so on until 100, then again 1,...,100,1,...,100, etc.

      • printGeneratedValues

        public PropertyChecker.Parameters printGeneratedValues()
        Enables verbose mode, when for every execution of property check all the generated values are printed to the stdout. If a check fails, this is also printed. Can be useful to get an impression of how good the generators are, and for debugging purposes.
        Returns:
        this

      • printRawData

        public PropertyChecker.Parameters printRawData()
        During shrinking, prints the raw underlying data used to feed generators. Rarely needed, requires some understanding of the checker internals.
        Returns:
        th

public PropertyChecker.Parameters recheckingIteration(long seed,

        Deprecated. To catch your attention. It's fine to call this method during test debugging, but it should not be committed to version control and used in regression tests, because any changes in the test itself or the framework can render the passed arguments obsolete. For regression testing, it's recommended to code the failing scenario explicitly.
        Checks the property within a single iteration by using specified seed and size hint. Useful to debug the test after it's failed, if rechecking(java.lang.String) isn't enough (e.g. due to unforeseen side effects).

      • checkScenarios

        public void checkScenarios(@NotNull
                           Supplier<? extends ImperativeCommand> command)
        Performs a check that the scenarios generated by the given command are successful. Default PropertyChecker settings are used.
        Parameters:
        command - a supplier for a top-level command. This supplier should not have any side effects.
